usic and Arts Festival]] 2005\n* [[Kraftwerk]]\n* [[Dan Snaith|Caribou]], [[Junior Boys]] and [[The Russian Futurists]]\n* [[The Books]], [[Keith Fullerton Whitman]] and [[Greg Davis (musician)|Greg Davis]]\n* [[DAT Politics]], [[Oly (band)|Oly]] and [[No Funeral]]\n* [[Autechre]] and Rob Hall\n* [[Prefuse 73]], [[Battles (band)|Battles]] and [[Four Tet]]\n* [[Yasanao Tone]], [[Tim Hecker]], [[Mark Stewart (musician)|Mark Stewart]], [[Aphex Twin]], [[Whitehouse (band)|Whitehouse]]\n{{col-3}}\n'''Gear reviews'''\n* [[Reaktor|NI Reaktor 5]]\n* [[Tascam|Tascam GigaStudio 3]]\n* [[NI Synthetic Drums 2]]\n* [[Propellerheads Reason|Propellerheads Reason 3]]\n* [[Kontakt (software)|NI Kontakt 2]]\n* [[M-Audio|M-Audio Trigger Finger]]\n* [[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer CDJ-200]]\n* [[Absynth|NI Absynth 3]]\n* [[Digidesign|Digidesign Synchronic]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grooves}}\n[[Category:American music magazines]]\n[[Category:American online magazines]]\n[[Category:American quarterly magazines]]\n[[Category:Dance music magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 2005]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Online magazines with defunct print editions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n|title = Grooves\n|image_file = GroovesLogo.png\n|image_size =\n|image_caption = ''Grooves'' logo (2005-current)\n|editor = Sean Portnoy\n|editor_title = Editor\n|staff_writer =\n|frequency = Quarterly\n|circulation = 10,000\n|category = [[Electronic music]]\n|company =\n|publisher = Sean Portnoy\n|founded= 1999\n|finaldate = December 2005\n|finalnumber = #18\n|country = United States\n|based = San Francisco\n|language = [[English language|English]]\n|website = [http://www.groovesmag.com/ www.groovesmag.com]\n|issn = 1555-3264\n}}\n\n'''''Grooves''''' is an American [[electronic music]] [[magazine]] founded in 1999 by editor [[Sean Portnoy]], initially concentrating on the then-burgeoning [[Intelligent dance music|IDM]] music genre and expanding to its more experimental, abstract offshoots, such as [[microsound]], [[microhouse]] and [[glitch]], eventually encompassing a global view of musicians and cross-cultural influences that is reflected in coverage of [[Junglist|jungle]], [[UK garage|two-step]], [[Alternative hip hop|avant rap]], [[broken beat]] and other offbeat new music. The headquarters is in San Francisco.<ref name=\"god\"/>\n\nEarly issues contained a vast range of full-length album and 12\" [[single (music)|single]]/[[Extended play|EP]] reviews; later issues added new media release types, including reviews of books and [[DVD]]-based documentary and music video film releases. Additionally, each issue contained several artist interviews and label profiles, evaluations of new and offbeat [[digital electronics|digital]] and [[analogue electronics|analog]] hardware and software tools for making electronic music, and coverage of live performances and festivals throughout the United States, Canada, South America and Europe.\n\n== Catalog ==\nThe first eighteen issues were printed and distributed worldwide through record stores and by subscription quarterly.<ref name=\"god\"/>  In December 2005, after 18 issues, the magazine switched to an exclusively online format.<ref name=\"god\">{{cite news|title=Grooves Magazine Fades Out Print, to Go Digital|url=http://www.foliomag.com/2005/grooves-magazine-fades-out-print-go-digital/|accessdate=24 February 2016|work=Folio|date=1 December 2005}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foliomag.com/viewmedia.asp?prmMID=5224&prmID=1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2007-07-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070507101846/http://www.foliomag.com/viewmedia.asp?prmMID=5224&prmID=1 |archive-date=2007-05-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The first two digital issues, were made available through a web-based interface provided by Texterity.<ref>http://www.texterity.com/</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20060213034004/http://www.groovesmag.com/news_item.php?id=00000008</ref> Podcasts and forums were added in mid-2006. Since then, features and review articles have been made available directly through the main site.<ref>http://www.groovesmag.com/</ref>\n\n=== Issue 01 ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''Features'''\n* [[Richard Devine]]\n* [[Wagon Christ]]\n* [[V/VM]]\n* [[Kid 606]]\n* [[Keith Whitman]]\n* [[Puppy (musician)|Puppy]]\n* [[Lexaunculpt]]\n* [[Slicker]]\n{{col-3}}\n'''Live reviews'''\n* [[Electric Company (musician)|Electric Company]] / [[Lexaunculpt]]\n* Chain Reaction Tour : [[Stefan Betke|Pole]] / Scion / [[Substance (musician)|Substance]] / Vainquer\n* [[CMJ Music Conference]] : [[Coldcut]] / [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]] / [[Talvin Singh]] / [[DJ Krush]] + [[Dub Tribe Sound System]]\n{{col-3}}\n'''Gear reviews'''\n* ''None''\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Issue 02 ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''Features'''\n* [[Funki Porcini]]\n* [[Not Breathing]]\n* [[Mark Pistel]]\n* [[Suction (musician)|Suction]]\n* [[Jake Mandell]]\n* [[Add N to (X)]]\n* [[Funkst\u00f6rung]]\n* [[Trans Am (band)|Trans Am]]\n{{col-3}}\n'''Live reviews'''\n* [[Winter Music Conference]]\n* [[Meat Beat Manifesto]] / [[Emergency Broadcast Network]] / [[Danny Zelonky|Low Res]]\n* [[Swayzak]]\n* [[Kurtis Mantronik]] / [[Cut Creator]] / [[Shortee & Faust]]\n{{col-3}}\n'''Gear reviews'''\n* ''None''\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Issue 03 ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''Features'''\n* [[Curd Duca]] and [[Headcase]]\n* [[Delarosa & Asora]]\n* [[Solenoid (musician)|Solenoid]]\n* [[Kracfive Records|Kracfive]]\n* [[Saundart]]\n* [[12K]]\n* [[Jega (musician)|Jega]]\n* [[Andrea Parker (DJ)|Andrea Parker]]\n* [[Mu-Ziq]]\n* [[Mego (label)|Mego Records]]\n* [[Neotropic]]\n{{col-3}}\n'''Live reviews'''\n* [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella Festival]]\n* [[Soundboy Yakuza Tour]]\n* [[Funkst\u00f6rung]]\n* [[808 State]]\n{{col-3}}\n'''Gear reviews